<h1>To Thomas Waggener</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">By George Washington Esquire; Colonel of the Virginia Regiment, &amp;c.<br/>To Captn Thomas Waggener.<br/>Sir,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">[Fort Loudoun, 29 July 1757]</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>You are Ordered forthwith to march from hence to the South-branch with your own men, and such of Capt. McKenzies as are at this place. The latter you are to deliver to him so soon as you arrive at this Garrison<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> (with the orders and Instructions herewith given you for him.)<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> And, immediately after he has taken a size and necessary roll of his company, you
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-04-02-pb-0349">[349]</span>
are to demand 25 men and an Officer, (if he can possibly spare one) to reinforce your command; and with them proceed to the post assigned you (namely, Butter-milk-fort) and there use your utmost endeavours to protect the numerous body of Inhabitants in all those parts.</p>
<p>I am sensible, there is a necessity of throwing a few soldiers into some of the country-forts, in order to detain the Inhabitants in them; and I approve of your doing it; but at the same time recommend, that no more be appointed for this Service, than what are absolutely necessary to detain the inhabitants, &amp; to resist any sudden attempts of the enemy to surprize the fort; reserving the principal part of them at the fort you reside at, to turn out and pursue the enemy, when you hear they are about it.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>You are, as soon as you arrive at Captn McKenzies Garrison, to dispatch a messenger to Captn Woodward, that he may hold himself in readiness to march immediately upon your arrival; (and to take with him the company lately belonging to Captn Bronaugh, which is now joined to his own).</p>
<p>You are also to inform the Officer (Lt Weeden) commanding the company, lately Captn Cockes, now joined to Captn Lewiss, that he is to march those men to Conogochieg immediately upon your arrival. And you are to see that not the least delay is made, after you do arrive in having this done.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>As all the companies, agreeably to their present regulation, are now supplied with Kettles from the public stores; you are desired to collect all the old ones, pots, &amp;c. that are among the troops upon the branch, and send them down to this place, under escort of Lt Weeden; giving him a strict charge to be careful of them: and you will deliver to Captn McKenzie, those which you have received at this place, for the use of his company.</p>
<p>You are, for farther direction, referred to the General Instructions herewith delivered to you.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> Given under my hand at Ft Loudoun, this 29th day of July, 1757.</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">G:W.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>The copyist should have written his garrison, not this Garrison. Capt. Robert McKenzie had been stationed with his men at Job Pearsals since August 1756 and was to remain there for some time.</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-04-02-pb-0350">[350]</span>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0227" class="document">GW to McKenzie</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0223" class="document">his Instructions to Company Captains, both this date</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0003">3</a>
   
   <p>Thomas Waggener had been stationed on the South Branch since January 1756 but since May had been at Fort Loudoun. When reducing the number of companies in the Virginia Regiment in May 1757, Dinwiddie specified that seventy men under Captain Waggener should be stationed in the neighborhood of Butter Milk Fort (<a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0086" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, 16 May 1757 [first letter]</a>). Buttermilk fort, one of a number of forts on the South Branch, was near the upper, or southern end of the Trough. In a Memorandum of 16 June 1757 to Col. John Stanwix and to Dinwiddie, GW indicated that there were twenty-eight men stationed at Buttermilk fort and that the fort was seventy-eight miles from Fort Loudoun. Waggeners company size roll probably for August 1757 was headed: at Fort Hollond and on the South Branch; on 14 Sept. and again on 1 Oct. 1757 Waggener submitted returns of provisions at Fort Hopewell. Fort Hopewell may have been Kuykendals fort, one of the rather numerous small forts on the South Branch, but the name Fort Holland crops up <span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: 'only' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2006-03-17]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>in the fall of 1757 <span class="choice addition" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Added &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2006-03-17]]&lt;/span&gt; ]">and the summer and fall of 1758,</span> and may well be a more formal name bestowed upon a fort with a name like Buttermilk. Fort Holland was probably named for Paymaster General Henry Fox, whose residence was Holland House in London.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>For the location and movements at this time of the companies of the Virginia Regiment commanded by Robert McKenzie, Henry Woodward, and Joshua Lewis, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0223&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-04-02-0223-fn-0001#GEWN-02-04-02-0223-fn-0001" class="document">GWs Instructions to Company Captains, this date, n.1.</a> Captains William Bronaugh and Thomas Cocke were at Fort Cumberland with their companies until the Maryland forces took over at that fort, and the two men lost their commands when the regiment was reduced to ten companies in May.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0225-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0223" class="document">Instructions to Company Captains, this date.</a></p>

</div> 
</div>
